Basics

xde_setup()

If we were doing primary model building. In RAMP, we are building models that borrow from others.

To make a model in exDE we use the xde_setup() functions.

xde_setup("rm") -> rm

xde_solve()

To solve it, we call xde_solve

xde_solve(rm, Tmax = 5*365, dt=5) -> rm
par(mfrow = c(2,1))
plot_PR(rm)
xde_plot_eir(rm)

options

We can easily modify the model by changing one of the parameters. Here, we do it by hand:

rm1 = rm
rm1$Lpar$Lt = function(t, pars){(1.01+sin(2*pi*t/365))^2} 
xde_steady(rm1) -> rm1
par(mfrow = c(2,1))
xde_plot_eir(rm1)
plot_PR(rm1)

xde_steady()

If the model reaches a steady state or a stable orbit, we would like to know what it looks like. The function xde_steady() is a wrapper around xde_solve. The function runs the simulation for several years (default = 10), and returns the orbits from the last year. In the following, we plot the orbits of the PR with respect to the EIR. The grey lines show the approach to the steaddy state. The stable orbit is in black.

xde_plot_eirXpr(rm1, clrs = grey(0.5))
xde_plot_eirXpr(rm1, steady=T, add =T)

if(!exists("rm1")) xde_steady(rm1) -> rm1
par(mfrow = c(1,3), mar = c(5,4,1,4))
xde_splot(rm1)

xde_scaling_eir = function(pars, N=3){
  stopifnot(pars$nPatches==1)
  F_eir_base = pars$F_eir
  scl_a = with(pars$Hpar, sum(wts_f*H)/sum(H))
  scl_b = integrate(F_eir_base, 0, 365, pars=pars)$value
  pars$scl = 1/scl_a/scl_b
  pars$F_eir = function(t, pars){with(pars,aeir*scl*F_eir_base(t, pars))}
  #pars$aeir = 1 
  #scl0 = integrate(pars$F_eir, 0, 365, pars=pars)$value
  eir = 10^seq(-1,3, length.out=N)
  pr = 0*eir
  scaling = list()  
  for(i in 1:N){
    pars$aeir = eir[i]
    xde_tmp <- xde_steady(pars)
    tmp <- xde_tmp$steady
    tot_pr <- with(tmp, rowSums(pr*H)/rowSums(H))
    scaling[[i]] = with(tmp, list(aeir=365*c(eir, eir[1]), eir=365*c(eir, eir[1]), pr=tot_pr, pr_i = tmp$pr)) 
    pr[i] = mean(tot_pr)
    #print(c(i=i))
    #if(i == 6) browser() 
  }
  pars$scaling <- scaling
  pars$eirpr <- list(aeir=eir, eir=eir/365, pr=pr) 
  pars$F_eir = F_eir_base
  return(pars)
}
xde_setup_cohort("sis", F_eir) -> sis
xde_scaling_eir(sis, 25) -> sis
with(sis$eirpr, plot(aeir, pr, type = "l", log="x"))

xde_pr2eir()

Since xde_scaling outputs the relationship between the EIR and the PR, we can invert it by simply inverting (with some interpolation):

xde_pr2eir = function(pr, pars){
  PR = pars$eirpr$pr 
  EIR = pars$eirpr$eir 
  ix = which(pr<max(PR) & pr>min(PR))
  get_eir = function(pr){
    ix = max(which(PR<pr)) 
    ff = (pr-PR[ix])/(PR[ix+1]-PR[ix])
    EIR[ix] + ff*(EIR[ix+1]-EIR[ix])
  }
  eir = 0*pr-1
  eir[ix] = sapply(pr[ix], get_eir)
  eirpr = list(pr=pr[ix], eir=eir[ix]) 
  if(length(ix)>0) eirpr$errors = c(pr=pr[-ix])
  return(eirpr) 
}

We can run this for 50 randomly chosen values of the PfPR.

preir_i = xde_pr2eir(runif(50, 0, 1), sis)

The function flags any values that are outside of the acceptable range. This may not seem important for the SIS model, but the range of other models can be bounded, so we don’t want to return nonsense values.

preir_i$errors
##        pr1        pr2 
## 0.02534094 0.98545080

We can plot the others:

plot(sis$eirpr$eir, sis$eirpr$pr, type = "l", log = "x")
points(sis$eirpr$eir, sis$eirpr$pr)
with(preir_i, points(eir, pr, pch = 19, col = "red"))

split_stratum()

In ~/mob_library/Stratification.Rmd we define the S3 function split_stratum_by_biting. Here, we use it to split a population into

sis2 = split_stratum_by_biting(sis, 1, .2, sqrt(10))
sis2 <- xde_solve(sis2)
xde_scaling_eir(sis2, 25) -> sis2

The shift mainly reflects the fact that 80% of the population is getting exposed at a lower level.

plot(sis$eirpr$aeir, sis$eirpr$pr, type = "l", log = "x", xaxt= "n", xlab = "aEIR", ylab = "PR")
axis(1, 10^(-1:3), c(0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000))
lines(sis2$eirpr$aeir, sis2$eirpr$pr, col = "darkred")

What is a model?

Model scoping

Scoping is the act of identifying a subset of elements within a larger set. When you scope a data model, you create a diagram to hold all the elements that are part of your scope. The diagram represents a view of your scope. Attributes that are part of the scope are highlighted with a color. Attributes that are not part of the scope are set as non-persistent.
